WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.882 --> 00:00:09.590
MALE SPEAKER: Good
afternoon, and welcome

00:00:09.590 --> 00:00:12.970
to Talks at Google in
Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:00:12.970 --> 00:00:17.850
Today it's my great pleasure
to introduce Beth Shapiro.

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:21.140
Dr. Shapiro is here today
to discuss her book,

00:00:21.140 --> 00:00:25.400
"How to Clone a Mammoth: The
Science of De-Extinction."

00:00:25.400 --> 00:00:29.400
We have the science today
to restore extinct species

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:31.710
to life, but should we?

00:00:31.710 --> 00:00:34.620
The ethical challenges
are enormous.

00:00:34.620 --> 00:00:39.160
Using DNA collected from
remains as a genetic blueprint,

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:43.070
scientists aim to engineer
extinct traits, traits

00:00:43.070 --> 00:00:45.040
that evolved by
natural selection

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:49.460
over thousands of years,
into living organisms.

00:00:49.460 --> 00:00:51.480
But rather than
viewing de-extinction

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:54.380
as a way to restore
one particular species,

00:00:54.380 --> 00:00:57.280
she argues that the
overarching goal

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:00.550
should be the revitalization
and stabilization

00:01:00.550 --> 00:01:04.280
of contemporary ecosystems.

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:07.620
Dr. Shapiro is an
evolutionary biologist

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:10.460
who integrates
molecular phylogenetics

00:01:10.460 --> 00:01:13.680
with advanced
computational biostatistics

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:17.620
to reconstruct the influences
on population dynamics

00:01:17.620 --> 00:01:20.410
in a wide variety of organisms.

00:01:20.410 --> 00:01:23.120
She is Associate
Professor of Ecology

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:27.640
and Evolutionary Biology
at UC Santa Cruz.

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:30.350
Her work has appeared in
numerous publications,

00:01:30.350 --> 00:01:34.770
including "Nature and Science,"
and she was a 2009 MacArthur

00:01:34.770 --> 00:01:36.680
Foundation Fellow.

00:01:36.680 --> 00:01:39.464
Please join me in
welcoming Beth Shapiro.

00:01:39.464 --> 00:01:40.750
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:40.750 --> 00:01:43.100
BETH SHAPIRO: Thank you.

00:01:43.100 --> 00:01:45.830
Well, thank you very much
for inviting me to come here,

00:01:45.830 --> 00:01:49.231
and for taking the time out
of your busy and hectic days

00:01:49.231 --> 00:01:50.730
to come and listen
to me, especially

00:01:50.730 --> 00:01:53.000
after David Duchovny,
who I'm sure was

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.460
quite entertaining, and
probably more entertaining

00:01:56.460 --> 00:01:57.840
than I can possibly be.

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:00.280
So let's just leave
it at that, right?

